There exist certain Christians, somewhat controversially termed "[Hyperdispensationalists](/Hyperdispensationalism)" (specifically, Mid-Acts dispensationalists), who accept only the [Epistles of Paul](/Epistles_of_Paul) as directly applicable to the church in the present age. Consequently, they do not consider water baptism a practice for the church today, arguing that [Paul](/Paul_the_Apostle), as [God](/God_in_Christianity)'s apostle to the nations, was explicitly *not* sent to baptize. A more extreme subset, Ultradispensationalists (Acts 28 dispensationalism), who even reject the practice of the [Lord's Supper](/Eucharist), similarly do not practice baptism, as these rites are not found in the later "Prison Epistles" [280]. Both these sects, however, believe that water baptism was a valid practice for covenant Israel. Hyperdispensationalists further assert that [Peter](/Saint_Peter)'s gospel message was distinct from [Paul](/Paul_the_Apostle)'s [281]. Hyperdispensationalists propose: [citation needed]

*   The [Great Commission](/Great_Commission) [282] and its associated baptism were directed specifically towards early Jewish believers, not the Gentile believers of the mid-Acts period or later.
*   The baptism described in Acts 2:36–38 is interpreted as [Peter](/Saint_Peter)'s call for Israel to repent of their complicity in the death of their [Messiah](/Messiah), rather than a Gospel announcement of [atonement](/Atonement_in_Christianity) for sin, which they consider a later doctrine revealed through [Paul](/Paul_the_Apostle).

Water baptism, as found early in the [Book of Acts](/Acts_of_the_Apostles), is, according to this view [citation needed], now supplanted by the "one baptism" [145] [non-primary source needed] that [John the Baptist](/John_the_Baptist) had foretold [283] [non-primary source needed]. Other proponents [who?] of this view distinguish between John's prophesied baptism by [Christ](/Christ_(title)) with the [Holy Spirit](/Holy_Spirit_in_Christianity) and the [Holy Spirit](/Holy_Spirit_in_Christianity)'s baptism of the believer *into* the body of [Christ](/Christ_(title)); the latter, they contend, is the "one baptism" relevant for today [citation needed]. This "one baptism" for the contemporary believer, it is asserted [by whom?], is the "baptism of the [Holy Spirit](/Holy_Spirit_in_Christianity)" that incorporates the believer into the Body of Christ, the church [284] [non-primary source needed].

Many within this group [who?] also argue that John's promised [baptism by fire](/Baptism_by_fire) is still pending [citation needed], referring to the eventual destruction of the world by fire [285] [non-primary source needed].

Other Hyperdispensationalists [which?] hold the belief that baptism was indeed necessary up until the mid-Acts period [citation needed]. It's a testament to how many ways one can interpret ancient texts, often leading to more division than clarity.

### Debaptism

*   Main article: [Debaptism](/Debaptism)

Most Christian churches, clinging to the doctrine of the [sacramental character](/Sacramental_character), view baptism as a singular, once-in-a-lifetime event that can neither be repeated nor undone. They maintain that those who have been baptized remain baptized, regardless of whether they later renounce the Christian faith by embracing a non-Christian religion or by completely [rejecting religion](/Irreligion). However, some organizations and individuals, in a rather futile gesture, are now engaging in the practice of "debaptism" [286]. One might wonder what they expect to achieve; a spiritual erasure isn't quite as simple as removing a record from a dusty parish book.

